Date: 3/7/1901
Source: Otago Witness
Author:
Vol / Page: 60
Edition:
Quote: When logs are to be hauled up to logging bank, a stout steel dog is driven into the end of the log, which lies on a broad steel shoe, and as the engine winds its load forward this shoe rides over every obstacle in the track until the log or logs (mostly two or three at a time) are brought out of the bush on to tram line to be conveyed to the sawmill.
